com.infinitydb.map.visitor

Class VisitableMapWrapper<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.Visitable<K,V>
      • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.VisitableMapWrapper<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - key type of wrapped map
    V - value type of wrapped map
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    VisitableMap<K,V>

    public class VisitableMapWrapper<K,V>
extends Visitable<K,V>
    Make any regular Map visitable as a series of key/value pairs using visit(). In Java 8, a forEach() exists already on every Map via the new default method in the Map interface, but this wrapper may allow improvements later such as threading and remoting.

    A visiting-aware Map can do an efficient internal visitation of its key/value pairs, but some regular Maps such as ConcurrentSkipListMap do not have an optimized forEach() and they just use the entrySet, which uses an Iterator and creates garbage just like this wrapper.

    This implementation of the wrapper simply iterates over the wrapped Map, using an algorithm that is effectively: 

     public void visit(MapVisitor< ? super K, ? super V> mapVisitor) {
     for (Entry< ? super K, ? super V> e : regularMap.entrySet()) {
         mapVisitor.visit((K)e.getKey(), (V)e.getValue());
     }
 }

    Note that even if the Map is capable of concurrency as well, because it implements ConcurrentMap, then it is still handled without parallelism. (At present).

    The normal pattern of use is like: 

     new VisitableMapWrapper(map).visit(new PrinterVisitor());
    However, until more features are added to VisitableMapWrapper, it is just as easy to do: 
     new PrinterVisitor().visit(anyKindOfMap);

    Which is even fewer lines of code than in the Iterator approach, and the PrinterVisitor is re-usable and usable with non-VisitableMaps.
